{marker description}{...}
{title:Description}

{p 4 4 2}
{cmd:bimpoisson} fits bivariate mixed Poisson regression models by the method
of maximum simulated likelihood (MSL), following the approaches proposed by 
Munkin and Trivedi (1999). To quote Munkin and Trivedi (`MT'), p. 35,  
"[w]e wish to to specify a general bivariate count model in which 
overdispersion comes through bivariate unobserved heterogeneity which affects 
the conditional mean functions. Assume that the two count variables 
{it:y}1 and {it:y}2 have a Poisson distribution conditional on 
the σ-fields generated by the random variables of unobserved heterogeneity 
{it:ε}1, {it:ε}2 and the set of independent explanatory variables {it:x}1 
and {it:x}2:

{center:{it:yj} | {it:xj}, {it:εj} ~ P({it:μj}), {it:μj} > O, {it:j} = l, 2,}

{p 4 4 2}
where we parameterize the mean parameters {it:μ}1 and {it:μ}2 as
exp({it:x}1'{it:ß}1 + {it:ε}1) and exp({it:x}2'{it:ß}2 + {it:ε}2), 
respectively. The unobservable variables {it:ε}1 and {it:ε}2 are 
assumed jointly normally distributed, i.e. 

{center:({it:ε}1, {it:ε}2) ~ N{(0, 0), ({it:σ}1^2, {it:ρσ}1{it:σ}2, {it:σ}2^2)}, 0 <= |ρ| <= 1."}

{p 4 4 2}
MT recommend using a robust variance estimator.

{p 4 4 2}
For an overview of alternative approaches to modelling bivariate count
data, and software, see Xu and Hardin (2016).
	
{p 4 4 2}
The default MSL estimator implemented in {cmd:bimpoisson} is that described 
by MT, p. 36, in which an importance sampling function is used to address 
the issue that maximization of the MSL function is problematic for values 
of |{it:ρ}| close to one. (Symptoms may include continuous "(backed up)"
messages in the iteration log or "r(430) convergence not achieved".) MT 
use a bivariate standard normal distribution with {it:ρ} = 0 as their 
sampling function. Like Jumamyradov and Munkin (2022), we use a sampling 
distribution that is bivariate normal with means zero, but with 
standard deviations unrestricted. With this approach, drawn values provide more 
effective coverage and improve MSL's estimation of the double integral 
that specifies the bivariate density of the bivariate mixed Poisson model. 
{cmd:bimpoisson} builds on this idea and also allows users to optionally set
a non-zero value for the sampling function correlation using the 
{cmd:rho_sf(#)} option. 

{p 4 4 2}
MT's MSL estimator not taking account of the maximization feasibility issue, 
described in their eq. (11), p. 35, is implemented by selecting 
{cmd:bimpoisson}'s {cmd:alt} option. 

{p 4 4 2} 
By default and following MT, {cmd:bimpoisson}'s two MSL estimators use 
pseudorandom numbers (draws from the standard uniform distribution) when 
simulating probabilities. Optionally, Halton draws can be used instead. 
(Jumamyradov and Munkin (2022) use Halton draws.) According to Train,
"[t]he superior coverage and the negative correlation over observations that 
are obtained with Halton draws combine to make Halton draws far more 
effective than random [uniform] draws for simulation" (2003, p. 231). Train
also states that "[d]iscarding the initial part of the sequence eliminates the 
correlation [between the initial terms of two Halton sequences]. The number of
initial elements to discard needs to be at least as large as the largest
prime that is used in creating the sequences (2003, p. 230)". By default,
{cmd:burn(#)} uses # = 5, noting that our sequences are created using the
first two primes (2, 3).

{p 4 4 2}
The default number of simulations is 10. This is a very low value and should
only be used for checking syntax. For serious modelling, the number of 
simulations is likely to be much larger. We recommend that users, having 
fitted a model with some specific number of simulations, increase the number 
systematically to check that estimates of the mixture distribution parameters 
in particular are robust. 

{p 4 4 2}
Antithetic acceleration is a variance reduction technique according to 
which negatively correlated draws are used instead of independently 
distributed random numbers. We follow MT (section 4.3, pp. 38-39) and 
create one antithetic draw for each draw by reversing the sign of both 
of the two elements. To implement antithetic acceleration, use the 
{cmd:antithetic} option. Antithetic acceleration is commonly used in 
conjunction with standard uniform draws. (It is almost never used together
with Halton draws.) 

{p 4 4 2}
MT (section 4.2, pp. 37-38) also implement a first-order method for correcting 
asymptotic bias in the MSL estimator. To implement this method, use the 
{cmd:bias} option. 

{p 4 4 2}
On the basis of their Monte-Carlo analysis of the MSL estimator using the
sampling function approach, MT (p. 40) report that "[t]he first-order 
correction of the asymptotic bias significantly reduces the number of 
simulations needed for the estimation up a given degree of bias. 
First-order corrected SML together with antithetic sampling produces 
most efficient estimates." Jumamyradov and Munkin (2022) provide more 
extensive analysis of potential bias, and how it varies with the true values
of the mixture distribution parameters.
	
{marker options}{...}
{title:Options}
{dlgtab:Main}

{phang}
{opt nsim(#)} sets number of simulations (default value is 10). 
Unless checking syntax, users should normally specify a much 
larger number{p_end}  
{phang}
{opt anti:thetic} uses antithetic acceleration, as described above.   
Given nsims({it:#}), the total number of simulations is 2{it:#} if 
this option is specified{p_end}   
{phang}
{opt ha:lton} uses Halton draws for simulation rather than the default which is 
standard uniform random draws{p_end}  
{phang}
{opt burn(#)} drop # initial elements when creating the Halton sequences 
(default is 5){p_end}  
{phang}
{opt bias} uses the first-order bias correction, as described above, and is 
recommended{p_end}   
{phang}
{opt seed(str)} sets the seed. Relevant only when using uniform draws. In this
case, users are recommended to set the seed for reproducibility. If no seed 
is set, the current rng state is used{p_end} 
{phang}
{opt rho_sf(#)} sets the sampling function correlation (default # = 0){p_end} 
{phang}
{opt alt} uses the alternative MSL estimation method (default uses sampling 
function{p_end} 
{phang}
{opt rng0} sets the random number generator (`rng') state back to its 
pre-estimation value: see {help rngstate}{p_end}  
{phang}

{dlgtab:Model}

{phang}
{opt noconstant}; see
{helpb estimation options##noconstant:[R] Estimation options}.

{phang}
{opth offset1(varname)}, {opt offset2(varname)},
{opt constraints(constraints)}; see
{helpb estimation options:[R] Estimation options}.

{dlgtab:SE/Robust}

